    {
      "type": "latex_inline",
      "content": "z^{i,j} = \\underset{c \\in \\{0,1\\}}{\\arg \\max} (\\log \\pi_c^{i,j} + g_c^{i,j})",
      "start": 20656,
      "end": 20734
    },
    {
      "type": "latex_inline",
      "content": "(1)\n\nwhere",
      "start": 20734,
      "end": 20750
    },
    {
      "type": "latex_inline",
      "content": "are i.i.d samples drawn from a standard Gumbel distribution which can be easily sampled using inverse transform sampling by drawing",
      "start": 20758,
      "end": 20895
    },
    {
      "type": "latex_inline",
      "content": "and computing",
      "start": 20921,
      "end": 20940
    },
    {
      "type": "latex_inline",
      "content": ". We further substitute this",
      "start": 20958,
      "end": 20991
    },
    {
      "type": "latex_inline",
      "content": "operation, since it is not differentiable, with a Softmax reparameterization trick, also known as Gumbel-Softmax trick, as:",
      "start": 21000,
      "end": 21129
    },
    {
      "type": "latex_inline",
      "content": "z_c^{i,j} = \\frac{\\exp((\\log \\pi_c^{i,j} + g_c^{i,j})/\\tau)}{\\sum_{v \\in \\{0,1\\}} \\exp((\\log \\pi_v^{i,j} + g_v^{i,j})/\\tau)}",
      "start": 21129,
      "end": 21255
    },
    {
      "type": "latex_inline",
      "content": "(2)\n\nwhere",
      "start": 21255,
      "end": 21270
    },
    {
      "type": "latex_inline",
      "content": "is the temperature parameter to control Gumbel-Softmax distribution's smoothness, as the temperature",
      "start": 21296,
      "end": 21402
    },
    {
      "type": "latex_inline",
      "content": "approaches 0, the Gumbel-Softmax distribution becomes identical to the one-hot categorical distribution. As the randomness of g is independent of",
      "start": 21406,
      "end": 21557
    },
    {
      "type": "latex_inline",
      "content": ", we can now directly optimize our gating control policy using standard gradient descent algorithms.\n\nCompared to the previous graph structure learning approaches, our proposed method significantly re",
      "start": 21560,
      "end": 21802
    },
    {
      "type": "latex_inline",
      "content": "since it requires no dot products among high-dimensional node embeddings. Additionally, the graph structure learning policy is able to automatically learn the global topological connections among all ",
      "start": 21840,
      "end": 22937
    },
    {
      "type": "latex_inline",
      "content": "(e.g., add, mean, or max) on the differences between nodes associated with all the edges emanating from each node. The updated output of IPConv at the *i*-th node is given by:",
      "start": 22944,
      "end": 23125
    },
    {
      "type": "latex_inline",
      "content": "\\mathbf{x}_{i}' = \\sum_{j \\in \\mathcal{N}(i)} h_{\\mathbf{\\Theta}}(\\mathbf{x}_{i}||\\mathbf{x}_{j} - \\mathbf{x}_{j}||\\mathbf{x}_{j} + \\mathbf{x}_{i})",
      "start": 23125,
      "end": 23274
    },
    {
      "type": "latex_inline",
      "content": "(3)\n\nwhere",
      "start": 23274,
      "end": 23289
    },
    {
      "type": "latex_inline",
      "content": "is chosen as summation in our method,",
      "start": 23296,
      "end": 23339
    },
    {
      "type": "latex_inline",
      "content": "denotes a neural network, i.e. MLPs (Multi-layer Perceptrons),",
      "start": 23349,
      "end": 23417
    },
    {
      "type": "latex_inline",
      "content": "represents the time series embedding of node i and || denotes the concatenation operation. We denote",
      "start": 23446,
      "end": 23552
    },
    {
      "type": "latex_inline",
      "content": "as the differences between nodes to *explicitly model the influence propagation delay* from node j to i, captured by the value difference at each timestamp of the time series embedding. We\n\n<span id=\"",
      "start": 23579,
      "end": 23948
    },
    {
      "type": "latex_inline",
      "content": "with the differences to work as a *scale benchmark* such that the model can learn the truly generalized impact to the other nodes brought by anomalies instead of extreme values. Intuitively, for any s",
      "start": 23975,
      "end": 24932
    },
    {
      "type": "latex_inline",
      "content": "to enhance the compactness of each node by minimizing the log-likelihood of the probability of a connection being established as",
      "start": 24945,
      "end": 25079
    },
    {
      "type": "latex_inline",
      "content": "\\mathcal{L}_s = \\sum_{1 \\le i, j \\le M, i \\ne j} \\log \\pi_1^{i,j} \\tag{4}",
      "start": 25079,
      "end": 25154
    },
    {
      "type": "latex_inline",
      "content": "Furthermore, to encourage better learning convergence, the *connection learning policy* is initialized with all nodes connected. We *warm up* the network weights by training with this *complete graph ",
      "start": 25154,
      "end": 26869
    },
    {
      "type": "latex_inline",
      "content": ", of the input series. The outputs of the first-level dilated convolutions are fed into the graph convolution module proposed above. Then the second-level layer applies dilated convolutions, with the ",
      "start": 26912,
      "end": 27196
    },
    {
      "type": "latex_inline",
      "content": "(notice here that the number of parameters remains the same, but the filter width has been \"widened\"). By setting multi-scale dilation sizes with a hierarchical learning style, abundant temporal repre",
      "start": 27239,
      "end": 28329
    },
    {
      "type": "latex_inline",
      "content": "with respect to sequence length. To tackle this challenge, in this section, we first briefly review the background of some recent development of multi-head attention mechanism and then propose a more ",
      "start": 28345,
      "end": 28841
    },
    {
      "type": "latex_inline",
      "content": "(with sequence length n and dimensionality d), the self-attention function firstly projects them into queries",
      "start": 28880,
      "end": 28995
    },
    {
      "type": "latex_inline",
      "content": ", keys",
      "start": 29036,
      "end": 29047
    },
    {
      "type": "latex_inline",
      "content": "and values",
      "start": 29088,
      "end": 29104
    },
    {
      "type": "latex_inline",
      "content": ", h times with different, learned linear projections to",
      "start": 29145,
      "end": 29205
    },
    {
      "type": "latex_inline",
      "content": "dimensions, respectively. Then a particular scaled dot-product attention was computed to obtain the weights on the values as:\n\nAttention(Q, K, V) = Softmax(",
      "start": 29229,
      "end": 29390
    },
    {
      "type": "latex_inline",
      "content": "\\frac{QK^T}{\\sqrt{d_k}}",
      "start": 29390,
      "end": 29415
    },
    {
      "type": "latex_inline",
      "content": ")V (5)\n\nMulti-head attention allows the model to jointly attend to information from different representation subspaces at different\n\n<span id=\"page-5-0\"></span>![](_page_5_Figure_1.jpeg)\n\n![](_page_5_",
      "start": 29415,
      "end": 30196
    },
    {
      "type": "latex_inline",
      "content": "MultiHead(\\mathbf{Q}, \\mathbf{K}, \\mathbf{V}) = Concat(head_1, \\cdots, head_h)W^O",
      "start": 30196,
      "end": 30279
    },
    {
      "type": "latex_inline",
      "content": "(6)\n\nin which, h is the number of total heads. Each head is defined as:",
      "start": 30279,
      "end": 30355
    },
    {
      "type": "latex_inline",
      "content": "head_i = Attention(\\mathbf{Q}W_i^Q, \\mathbf{K}W_i^K, \\mathbf{V}W_i^V)",
      "start": 30355,
      "end": 30426
    },
    {
      "type": "latex_inline",
      "content": "(7)\n\nwhere the projections are parameter matrices",
      "start": 30426,
      "end": 30481
    },
    {
      "type": "latex_inline",
      "content": ".\n\nGlobal-learned Attention. Recent research [48], [49] claim that the self-attention in Transformers can be substantially simplified with trivial attentive patterns at training time: only preserving ",
      "start": 30645,
      "end": 31523
    },
    {
      "type": "latex_inline",
      "content": "(m > n) as a learnable global compatibility function across all training samples following the Synthesizer [51]. Hence, each head adds",
      "start": 31562,
      "end": 31702
    },
    {
      "type": "latex_inline",
      "content": "parameters while reducing two projection matrices",
      "start": 31705,
      "end": 31760
    },
    {
      "type": "latex_inline",
      "content": ". The attention now has been as following:",
      "start": 31775,
      "end": 31822
    },
    {
      "type": "latex_inline",
      "content": "Attention(S, V) = Softmax(S)V",
      "start": 31822,
      "end": 31853
    },
    {
      "type": "latex_inline",
      "content": "(8)\n\nwhere S is a learnable matrix which can be randomly initial-\n\nMulti-branch Architecture for Transformers. [52] has demonstrated the effectiveness of multi-branch attention in capturing global and",
      "start": 31853,
      "end": 33432
    },
    {
      "type": "latex_inline",
      "content": "\\mathbf{A}^{(1)}, \\mathbf{A}^{(2)}",
      "start": 33432,
      "end": 33468
    },
    {
      "type": "latex_inline",
      "content": "\\mathbf{A}^{(1)} = \\text{MultiHead}(\\mathbf{X}^{(1)})",
      "start": 33476,
      "end": 33531
    },
    {
      "type": "latex_inline",
      "content": "\\mathbf{A}^{(2)} = \\text{Global}(\\mathbf{X}^{(2)})",
      "start": 33535,
      "end": 33587
    },
    {
      "type": "latex_inline",
      "content": "(9)\n\nwhere",
      "start": 33587,
      "end": 33602
    },
    {
      "type": "latex_inline",
      "content": "\\mathbf{X}^{(1)} \\in \\mathcal{R}^{n \\times d_1}",
      "start": 33602,
      "end": 33651
    },
    {
      "type": "latex_inline",
      "content": ".\n\nIn our models, we only change the branch that captures the global contexts while remaining the local pattern extractor using either lightConv or dynamicConv [53].\n\nComputation Analysis. Table I lis",
      "start": 33726,
      "end": 34013
    },
    {
      "type": "latex_inline",
      "content": "refers to the total number of parameters in one selfattention module excluding the feed-forward layer. Obviously, compared to the original scaled dot-production, the amount of computation of global-le",
      "start": 34021,
      "end": 34530
    },
    {
      "type": "latex_inline",
      "content": ", the global attention module is more computationally efficient than the other variants.\n\n#### E. Anomaly Scoring\n\nInspired by [54], the original multivariate time series inputs are split into two par",
      "start": 34548,
      "end": 35110
    },
    {
      "type": "latex_inline",
      "content": "| # Mult-Adds                                                                                                                                | Global/Inter            |\n|------------------------------",
      "start": 35118,
      "end": 35670
    },
    {
      "type": "latex_inline",
      "content": "| Inter<br>Global<br>Both |\n\n<span id=\"page-6-0\"></span>instantly predicts output elements in a generative style. Let the single-step prediction denote as",
      "start": 35856,
      "end": 36015
    },
    {
      "type": "latex_inline",
      "content": ". We apply the Mean Square Error (MSE) between the predicted outputs",
      "start": 36060,
      "end": 36133
    },
    {
      "type": "latex_inline",
      "content": "and the observation",
      "start": 36149,
      "end": 36174
    },
    {
      "type": "latex_inline",
      "content": ", as the loss function to minimize:",
      "start": 36185,
      "end": 36225
    },
    {
      "type": "latex_inline",
      "content": "\\mathcal{L}_{mse} = \\frac{1}{M} \\sum_{t=1}^{n} ||\\mathcal{Y}^{(t)} - \\hat{\\mathcal{Y}}^{(t)}||_{2}^{2}",
      "start": 36225,
      "end": 36329
    },
    {
      "type": "latex_inline",
      "content": "(10)\n\nSimilar to the loss objective, the anomalous score compares the expected value at time t to the observed value, computing an anomaly score via the deviation level as:",
      "start": 36329,
      "end": 36507
    },
    {
      "type": "latex_inline",
      "content": "\\hat{\\mathbf{y}}^{(t)} = \\sum_{i=1}^{M} ||\\mathcal{Y}_i^{(t)} - \\hat{\\mathcal{Y}}_i^{(t)}||_2^2",
      "start": 36507,
      "end": 36604
    },
    {
      "type": "latex_inline",
      "content": "(11)\n\nFinally, we label a timestamp t as an anomaly if",
      "start": 36604,
      "end": 36664
    },
    {
      "type": "latex_inline",
      "content": "exceeds a fixed threshold. Since different approaches could be employed to set the threshold such as extreme value theory [38], the same anomaly detection model could result in different prediction pe",
      "start": 36686,
      "end": 39421
    },
    {
      "type": "latex_inline",
      "content": "|  |\n| Training size (normal data)             | 49619                      | 120899        |  |\n| <b>Testing size (data with attacks)</b> | 44931                      | 17219         |  |\n| Anomaly r",
      "start": 39461,
      "end": 40774
    },
    {
      "type": "latex_inline",
      "content": "\\tilde{x} = \\frac{x - \\min X_{train}}{\\max X_{train} - \\min X_{train}} \\tag{12}",
      "start": 40774,
      "end": 40855
    },
    {
      "type": "latex_inline",
      "content": "are the maximum value and the minimum value of the training set respectively.\n\n2) Evaluation metrics: We adopt the standard evaluation metrics in anomaly detection tasks, namely Precision, Recall and ",
      "start": 40905,
      "end": 41175
    },
    {
      "type": "latex_inline",
      "content": "Precision = \\frac{TP}{TP + FP}",
      "start": 41175,
      "end": 41207
    },
    {
      "type": "latex_inline",
      "content": "Recall = \\frac{TP}{TP + FN}",
      "start": 41217,
      "end": 41246
    },
    {
      "type": "latex_inline",
      "content": "F1 = 2 \\times \\frac{\\text{Precision} \\times \\text{Recall}}{\\text{Precision} + \\text{Recall}}",
      "start": 41256,
      "end": 41350
    },
    {
      "type": "latex_inline",
      "content": "(15)\n\nwhere TP represents the truly detected anomalies (aka. true positives), FP stands for the falsely detected anomalies (aka. false positives), TN represents the correctly classified normal samples",
      "start": 41350,
      "end": 42790
    },
    {
      "type": "latex_inline",
      "content": "(best F1) | -4.55%       | +29.33%      | +12.35%  |\n|          | PCA                           | 39.53        | 5.63         | 0.10     |\n|          | KNN                           | 7.76         | 7",
      "start": 42807,
      "end": 43736
    },
    {
      "type": "latex_inline",
      "content": "(best F1) | -13.94%      | +108.04%     | +47.37%  |\n\nBest performance in bold. Second-best with underlines.",
      "start": 43753,
      "end": 43867
    },
    {
      "type": "latex_inline",
      "content": "represents the percentage increase between our best F1-score performance and the second-best method (GDN).\n\nTABLE V: Experimental results on SMAP and MSL.\n\n<span id=\"page-7-1\"></span>\n\n| Method   |   ",
      "start": 43884,
